<process draft="false" dev-studio-version="7.6.02.02">
  <process-def name=":AutoPilot-OA-Common_Utilities:Format Date to Epoch Date">
    <parameters>
      <input global="false" required="true">
        <description>Date string

E.g. 

Tue Dec 06 16:52:24 CST 2011

2011/12/29 </description>
        <from>date</from>
        <to>date</to>
      </input>
      <input global="false" required="false">
        <description>The pattern describing the date and time format

e.g.

dd/mm/yyyy
EEE MMM dd hh:mm:ss zzz yyyy</description>
        <from>format string</from>
        <to>format string</to>
      </input>
      <input global="false" required="false">
        <description>The locale language argument is a valid ISO Language Code. These codes are the lower-case, two-letter codes as defined by ISO-639. You can find a full list of these codes at a number of sites, such as: 
http://www.ics.uci.edu/pub/ietf/http/related/iso639.txt

Some example below:

el Greek
en English
eo Esperanto
es Spanish
fr French
</description>
        <from>locale language</from>
        <to>locale language</to>
      </input>
      <input global="false" required="false">
        <description>The locale country argument is a valid ISO Country Code. These codes are the upper-case, two-letter codes as defined by ISO-3166. You can find a full list of these codes at a number of sites, such as: 
http://www.chemie.fu-berlin.de/diverse/doc/ISO_3166.html

For example:

MEXICO                                          MX 
MALAYSIA                                        MY
SPAIN                                           ES
UNITED STATES                                   US 

</description>
        <from>locale country</from>
        <to>locale country</to>
      </input>
      <output global="false" required="true">
        <to>epoch date</to>
        <from>epoch date</from>
      </output>
    </parameters>
    <access />
    <sequence>
      <switch>
        <meta>
          <documentation />
